{{Infobox terrorist attack |title=The Death of Adele Biton |partof=the [[Israeli–Palestinian conflict]] |map= |image = File:AdeleBitonFuneral.JPG |caption= Adele Biton Funeral. February 18, 2015 |location=Near [[Kifl Haris|Kif el-Hares]], West Bank |target= |date=14 March 2013 |time-begin= |time-end= |timezone= |type= Attack on vehicle with 4 passengers |fatalities= 1 |perps = Five Palestinians<ref>{{cite news|title=Toddler dies two years after stone-throwing incident left her critically injured|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.642948|publisher=[[Haaretz]]|date=17 February 2015}}</ref> |weapons= Projectiles (stones) }}
The '''death of Adele Biton''' occurred on 17 February 2015<ref name=Ynet100>{{cite news|title=Hundreds attend funeral for 4-year-old terror victim Adele Biton|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4628171,00.html|publisher=Ynet}}</ref> as a consequence of a March 14, 2013 [[Palestinian stone-throwing]] attack caused the civilian vehicle in which the infant Adele was riding to crash.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ross|first1=Adam|title=Mother of Adelle Bitton: Prayers Work!|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/172865#.VFezeofXOHk|accessdate=3 November 2014|publisher=Arutz Sheva|date=15 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Newman|first1=Marissa|title=Wounded 4-year-old to remain hospitalized|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/court-wounded-4-year-old-to-remain-hospitalized|accessdate=3 November 2014|publisher=Times of Israel|date=10 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Newman|first1=Marissa|title=Mother of injured toddler faces assailants in court|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/mother-of-injured-toddler-faces-assailants-in-court|accessdate=3 November 2014|publisher=Times of Israel|date=13 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=AdeleBitonDiesAgeFour>{{cite web|title=Adele Biton dies at age four|url=http://mfa.gov.il/MFA/ForeignPolicy/Terrorism/Victims/Pages/Adele-Biton.aspx|publisher=Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref>
==Incident== On the 14 March 2013, Adele, with her mother Adva and two sisters, Avigail and Naama, were in a car driving on Route 5 between the [[Israeli settlement]] of [[Yakir]] and [[Tel Aviv]],<ref name="Levinson" /> where the family had visited a grandmother. The Biton family were driving on Route 5 towards Tel Aviv.<ref name="Levinson" /> Palestinians were [[Criminal rock throwing|throwing stones at vehicles]] on the road at the time.<ref name=LevinsonRockThrowing>{{cite news|last1=Levinson|first1=Chaim|title=Israeli Infant Critically Hurt in Traffic Accident Caused by Stone-throwing Palestinians|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/israeli-infant-critically-hurt-in-traffic-accident-caused-by-stone-throwing-palestinians-1.509492|accessdate=27 September 2015|publisher=[[Haaretz]]|date=14 March 2013}}</ref> They were targeted by rock-throwers, and the car spun out of control and smashed into a truck which was parked on the side of the road, having stopped for similar reasons.<ref name="Levinson" /> The first health aide to arrive on the scene was a Palestinian volunteer paramedic, Muawiya Qabha, an Arab-Muslim volunteer paramedic, who gave immediate assistance. Soon afterwards he was joined by an Israeli doctor who happened to be driving by, who examined Adele and pronounced her clinically dead. Qabha, convinced he could save her life, continued to work on her, and after a considerable time, the girl began to respond. The child had suffered severe head injuries as a result of the crash and was hospitalized at the [[Rabin Medical Center]]'s Schneider Children's Medical Center for emergency surgery. She remained semi-comatose for two months, and was released to return to the family home.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toddler injured in terror attack fights for her life|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4360754,00.html}}</ref>
Adele never recovered from her injuries.<ref name=Levinson>{{cite news|last1=Levinson|first1=Chaim|title=Toddler dies two years after stone-throwing incident left her critically injured Adelle Biton never fully recovered from attack|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.642948|accessdate=22 February 2015|publisher=Haaretz|date=17 February 2015}}</ref> According to the ''[[New York Times]]'', Adele, "Biton, became a potent national symbol of the dangers that stones can cause".<ref name=Rudoren>{{cite news|last1=Rudoren|first1=Jodi|title=Israeli Girl Injured in Palestinian Rock-Throwing Attack in 2013 Dies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/18/world/middleeast/israeli-girl-injured-in-palestinian-rock-throwing-attack-in-2013-dies.html?_r=0|accessdate=22 February 2015|publisher=New York Times|date=17 February 2015}}</ref> According to ''New York Times'' reporter Jodi Rudoren, Adele was "among the victims who become somewhat iconic... Many, many articles were written about her."<ref name=Hollander>{{cite web|last1=Hollander|first1=Rikki|title=The Death of Adele Biton and The New York Times’ Justification of Lopsided Reporting|url=http://www.camera.org/index.asp?x_context=2&x_outlet=35&x_article=2945|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>
Biton is remembered as one of a long series of people injured and killed as a result of Palestinian rock-throwing at passing vehicles.<ref name=FreundMichael>{{cite news|last1=Freund|first1=Michael|title=A country held hostage by lawyers|url=http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Fundamentally-Freund-A-country-held-hostage-by-lawyers-417933|accessdate=25 September 2015|publisher=Jerusalem Post|date=24 September 2015}}</ref> Others who have suffered the same fate include Esther Ohana, a 20-year-old girl who was driving to her wedding rehearsal when she was murdered, eleven-year-old Chava Wechsberg, and [[Deaths of Asher and Yonatan Palmer|Asher Palmer]], a young father murdered along with his eleven-month-old son.<ref>Stephen M. Flatow,[http://njjewishnews.com/article/26294/for-victim-adele-biton-palestinian-rock-throwing-is-murder-not-resistance#.VPCgHcYqqqQ 'For victim Adele Biton, Palestinian rock-throwing is murder, not ‘resistance’,] [[New Jersey Jewish News]], February 20, 2015.</ref>According to historian [[Rafael Medoff]], 14 people have been killed by Palestinian stone throwing, including 3 Arabs mistaken for Jews by the rock throwers.<ref name=Medoff>[[Rafael Medoff]], [http://www.jns.org/latest-articles/2015/5/3/baltimore-riot-mom-needed-in-jerusalem#.VUmBPY6qqko= 'Baltimore ‘riot mom’ needed in Jerusalem,'] [[JNS.org]] 3 May 2015</ref>
==Arrests== 5 Palestinian teenagers, Muhammad Mahdi Suleiman,Tamer Ayyad Ahmad Souf, Ammar Abd al-Nayif Souf, Ali Yassin Ali Shamlawi and Muhammad Jumaa Muhammad Kleib, from [[Kfar Haras]] were arrested for throwing the rocks that caused the crash.<ref name=FiveTeensArrested>{{cite news|last1=Harel|first1=Amos|title=Five Teens Arrested for Stoning Car, Critically Injuring Baby|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/five-teens-arrested-for-stoning-car-critically-injuring-baby.premium-1.511701|accessdate=27 September 2015|publisher=Haaretz|date=24 March 2013}}</ref> They were charged with having thrown stones on that road that day. 20 drivers driving on that route during the day later filed insurance claims for damages to their vehicles, but no eyewitnesses, according to [[Ma'an News Agency]], were forthcoming, and no police station received complaints at the time. All five eventually confessed but retracted their statements in court, stating that their admissions had been extracted after repeated abuse under interrogation. In December 2015, all 5 were sentenced to 15 years in prison and fined $7,700.<ref>[http://www.maannews.com/Content.aspx?id=769421 'After 2 years behind bars, 'Hares boys' sentenced to 15 years,'] [[Ma'an News Agency]] 19 December 2015.</ref>
