{{Use British English|date=June 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Ellie Butler | birth_name = Ellie Butler | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|2006|12|30}} | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2013|10|28|2006|12|30}} | death_cause = Beating | nationality = [[British nationality law|British]] | other_names = | known_for = Murder victim }}
'''Ellie Butler''' (30 December 2006 – 28 October 2013) was a British girl who was [[murder]]ed by her father, Ben Butler, on 28 October 2013, at his home in [[Sutton, London]].<ref name="Ellie Butler Murder: How the full tragic story unfolded">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/21/ellie-butler-murder-how-the-full-tragic-story-unfolded/ | title=Ellie Butler Murder | author=Martin Evans|work=[[Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref> In February 2007, he was arrested after Ellie Butler was taken to a hospital with head and [[retina]]l injuries.<ref name="Ellie Butler murder: how the case unfolded">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jun/21/ellie-butler-how-the-case-unfolded | title=Ellie Butler murder|work=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref> Ellie then lived with her maternal grandparents until late 2012, when a judge, [[Mary Hogg|Justice Mary Hogg]], ordered she be returned to her parents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Diane Taylor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jun/22/ellie-butler-had-begged-not-to-be-sent-back-to-her-parents-says-aunt |title=Ellie Butler had begged not to be sent back to her parents, says aunt &#124; Society |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/judge-who-returned-ellie-butler-to-father-told-she-would-have-blood-on-her-hands-1.2693434 |title=Judge who returned Ellie Butler to father told she would have ‘blood on her hands’ |website=Irishtimes.com |date=2016-06-21 |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1715782/murdered-ellie-butlers-family-demand-inquiry |title=Murdered Ellie Butler's Family Demand Inquiry |website=News.sky.com |date=2016-06-22 |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>
On 21 June 2016, Ben Butler was found guilty of murder at the [[Old Bailey]] in London, and sentenced to a minimum of 23 years in prison.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36587103|title=Ben Butler jailed for murdering daughter Ellie after custody battle|publisher=BBC News|date=21 June 2016}}</ref> His partner and Ellie's mother, Jennie Gray, was jailed for 42 months in connection with the case, after admitting [[perverting the course of justice]], and both were found guilty of [[child cruelty]].<ref name=bbc/>
In the wake of Ellie's death and before the trial of Ben Butler and Jennie Gray, Sutton Safeguarding Children Board (SCCB) conducted a Serious Case Review into Ellie Butler's death. Beyond furnishing the Serious Case Review with necessary court orders, Hogg and other members of the judiciary refused to cooperate with it.<ref>{{Cite web |last1= Taylor |first1= Diane |last2= O'Carroll |first2= Lisa |date= 22 June 2016 |title= Ellie Butler judge 'took unwarranted steps' to reunite her with violent parents |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jun/22/ellie-butler-judge-took-unwarranted-steps-to-reunite-her-with-violent-parents |website= theguardian.com |accessdate= 22 June 2016 }}</ref>
The report of the Serious Case Review was published on 21 June 2016, immediately after Ben Butler's conviction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.suttonlscb.org.uk/files/professionalsdocs/SSCB%20CHILD%20D%20OVERVIEW%20REPORT.pdf|title=SCCB CHILD D OVERVIEW REPORT.pdf|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>. Launching the Report, Christine Davies, the Chair of SCCB, said: :"The serious case review concluded that the Family Court’s decision to exonerate Ben Butler of harming Ellie in 2007, combined with its subsequent order for agencies to be sent a letter to that effect, had a very significant impact on how agencies could protect his children from that point in time onwards.
:"Ben Butler’s exoneration and the Judge’s statement about him being a victim of a miscarriage of justice had the effect of handing all the power to the parents."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.careappointments.co.uk/practice-reports/item/39896-report-sutton-safeguarding-children-board-ellie-butler-serious-case-review|title=Report: Sutton Safeguarding Children Board - Ellie Butler Serious Case Review |access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>
