{{Taxobox | image = Eoph_MagelaT_site2.jpg | image_caption = ''[[Eophreatoicus]]'', a freshwater isopod from [[Kakadu National Park]], [[Australia]] | regnum = [[Animal]]ia | phylum = [[Arthropod]]a | subphylum = [[Crustacean|Crustacea]] | classis = [[Malacostraca]] | ordo = [[Isopoda]] | subordo = '''Phreatoicidea''' | subordo_authority = [[Thomas Roscoe Rede Stebbing|Stebbing]], 1893&nbsp;<ref>{{ITIS |id=331607 |taxon=Phreatoicidea}}</ref> | subdivision_ranks = [[Family (biology)|Families]] | subdivision = *[[Amphisopodidae]] <!--*[[Hypsimetopidae]]--> *[[Hypsimetopodidae]] *[[Mesamphisopidae]] *[[Palaeophreatoicidae]]† *[[Phreatoicidae]] *[[Ponderellidae]] }}
'''Phreatoicidea''' is a [[suborder]] of [[isopod]] [[crustacean]]s. Extant species are confined to [[fresh water|freshwater]] environments in [[South Africa]], [[India]], and [[Oceania]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crustacea.net/crustace/www/phreatoi.htm |title=Phreatoicidea (Isopoda, Peracarida, Malacostraca) |work=Crustacea: The Higher Taxa |publisher=[[Australian Museum]] |author=J. K. Lowry |accessdate=February 20, 2009}}</ref> This seemingly [[Gondwana]]-derived distribution belies the fact that the group once had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]]; fossils which can be assigned to the Phreatoicidea are the oldest isopod fossils, and are found throughout the world.<ref name="Brusca">{{cite web |author=Richard Brusca |date=August 6, 1997 |title=Isopoda |url=http://tolweb.org/Isopoda/6320/1997.08.06 |publisher=[[Tree of Life Web Project]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |year=1970 |volume=169 |issue=3948 |pages=854–855 |doi=10.1126/science.169.3948.854 |title=Isopod from the Pennsylvanian of Illinois |author=[[Frederick R. Schram]] |pmid=5432581}}</ref> In the intervening 325 million years, phreatoicideans have changed little, and are thus considered [[living fossil]]s.<ref name="Wilson">{{cite web |url=http://www-personal.usyd.edu.au/~buz/popular.html |title=About phreatoicidean isopods in Australia |author=Buz Wilson |publisher=[[University of Sydney]] |accessdate=February 20, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908072320/http://www-personal.usyd.edu.au/~buz/popular.html |archivedate=September 8, 2008 |df= }}</ref>
The first [[Australia]]n phreatoicidean was described by [[Charles Chilton (zoologist)|Charles Chilton]] in 1891.<ref name="Wilson"/> Two families are represented in Australia: [[Amphisopodidae]] in the interior of Australia, and in the west, and [[Phreatoicidae]] in [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and [[Tasmania]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www-personal.usyd.edu.au/~buz/map.html |title=Localities of Australian Phreatoicidea |author=Buz Wilson |publisher=[[University of Sydney]] |accessdate=February 20, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008003726/http://www-personal.usyd.edu.au/%7Ebuz/map.html |archivedate=October 8, 2008 |df= }}</ref>
